commentBody:
@Steven M. 

Of course there's no indication of a rebus (other than the fact that there's not enough space for some of the answers. That's all the hint we get.

I can see your point if you meant to call "STACK" a stealth rebus because the word never appears in the puzzle, but it became pretty obvious that it was implied.

@Trish 
That's odd, it should consider the puzzle complete and correct even with just the S.

If the timer is still running but the puzzle won't let you edit, clear the grid and enter your answers again. Make sure you leave an empty square that is not a rebus to fill in last.

@dutchiris 

I love the Maltese Falcon, Dutch, but didn't see any tie-in to it in the grid -- did you? Regardless, what a great movie, Peter Lorre is wonderful to watch, and  Elisha Cook Jr. as "the gunsel" is perfect casting. OK, I'm adding it to my Bogart fest.

DAUBS, which in Boston might be pronounced DOBBS, might summon "Treasure of Sierra Madre" for some, but it's a little TOO FAR...

@Vaer 

Hi Vaer! Good catch. I'm seeing things again!





I'm even thankful for emus...we need guardrails here, too, just like in the Outside World...

@B 
"Shoving letters into a box" makes it sound like an afterthought, which rebuses are definitely not. They are carefully constructed and thought out, the grid is made to fit the theme, not the other way around. I find them clever and enjoyable, and think they take a lot more work than a regular crossword. 

I'm just trying to convert you to my rebus cult.  :)

@Janine 

Like you, I've never understood the classification of a rebus as lazy when it's actually the opposite for the constructor. 

I've also never understood "cheating" as applied to a constructor. Constructors are writing for solvers of a certain skill level, and they want these people to solve and enjoy the puzzle. It's not constructor versus solver. If you find a puzzle too hard, it's above your skill level, and there's nothing wrong with that.  We've all been there.

@G.T. 
Somehow I always thought a hay ride meant sitting on a pile of hay, but when I finally got to go on one, the hay was all neatly baled. So it just felt like sitting anywhere else, plus hay prickles.

And it wasn't haunted.

@Justin 

Let's call 5280 feet a Justin then 🤣

I live at 104 m above sea level. I just checked at what altitude our highest settlement lies - the village Ząb sits at 1013 m, so way below you.

@Nancy J. 

I must disagree that S is the only letter that makes sense in that spot. E, L, Y, and several others could 'work' with 2 unfamiliar names. 

If you're already familiar with a name, great! But I'm much more liberal with the definition of Natick and believe it is in the eye of the beholder. I'm just happy I happened to choose S and didn't need to run through the alphabet.

@Rusty Wheelhouse 
Our solution has been "personal turkeys" in the form  of Cornish game hens.  Not too much in the way of left-overs, no all-day roasting, plenty of room left for the pecan pie...  

Memories flavor every dish.

@Teresa 

I think Native Americans might object to your post?

Also, some 7,7 billion non-American people do not celebrate the holiday.

@Andrzej 
Oh nuts, should I now be qualifying every salutation? "Good morning, if you see it as such". "Have a safe trip home, if that is your desire".  "Have a good 4th, (inhale) ifyouappreciatethecontributionsandsacrificesofthepeoplededicatedtotheconstitutionaldemocracyoftheunitedstatesofamerica." 
I confess that I have not been doing so.

@Hanson

Oversimplification and exaggeration logical fallacies, eh? Do those work on anybody who is older than 5?

No, of course not - YOU don't have to qualify everything - but you also probably should not expect others to refrain from qualifying: especially a person who represents a major newspaper that might actually get into well deserved trouble for not qualifying.

@Teresa 
For years --being respectful of religious diversity--I struggled with whether to say "Merry Christmas!" to persons who weren't Christian, or whose faith I was unsure of. I came to the decision that the words themselves were in reality an expression of my personal Good Will, which should be given universally, to persons of all faiths, and not disrespectful of any. (Although I may now prefix it with "I respect that Christmas may not be your holiday, but . . .")

Most, if not all, cultures have some sort of harvest or thanksgiving festival, many religious of nature, some purely secular, on different dates, but usually around the crop-harvests. Thanksgiving (on the last Thursday of November) is purely American, but gratitude is, or should be, universal.

@Helen Wright. In some places pancakes are served in stacks which can be of varying heights. A SHORT STACK is one with only two or three. 
.
Emus prefer waffles.

@RozzieGrandma 

Old Monty Python skit about the infamous Piranha Brothers.

<a href="https://getyarn.io/yarn-clip/30e73112-2b52-4853-b0f6-beb3cff7623d" target="_blank">https://getyarn.io/yarn-clip/30e73112-2b52-4853-b0f6-beb3cff7623d</a>

@Deb Amlen 

"But we have film of him nailing your head to the floor."

"Yeah, he did that."

@JohnWM 

OxyClean spray.  Then a DAUB of blue Dawn liquid detergent.  Then rub gently.  Wash as usual.  Voila!  

Ditto for gravy, red wine, and blood.

@Mean Old Lady 
Cranberry sauce, gravy, red wine, and blood! Clearly your Thanksgivings get a little bit, um, eventful.

(Is it Klingon Thanksgiving? IYKYK)

@Steve L 

Is there a time limit on that, though? Does it need to be done within 24 hours?

When I travel, it's not time changes I need to worry about, but getting wrapped up in the whirlwind of family and forgetting all else.

@Steve L 

I don’t know what the time limit is, but there is one. 

I didn’t solve the puzzles when the tech workers went on strike. The first puzzle I did after they went back to work was the first one I skipped. It was a week old and I got a blue star on finishing it.

@Steve L 
@Jen

I was on a seven day cruise with no WiFi, and my streak was toast, even with solving the puzzles in order when I got back. However, you can always ask the folks at NYTgames, and in my case, after a few emails, my streak was back, thanks to their help.

@Harriet Will is doing great. He’s still recovering, but he is editing some of the puzzles and you should see his byline on some of them in January. 

Here’s an article about what happened to him and how he’s recovering:

<a href="https://www.brainandlife.org/articles/crossword-editor-will-shortz-says" target="_blank">https://www.brainandlife.org/articles/crossword-editor-will-shortz-says</a>

@Deb Amlen

Thanks for the update on Will Shortz! It’s great to hear that he’s back at work.

Joel Fagliano is doing a fine job, but it will be nice to see Will’s byline again.

@Harriet 

I'm pretty sure Will is still doing the NPR Sunday Puzzle, so you can check in on him there. 

Happy Thanksgiving!

@Rich in Atlanta 
Happy to be here and hear from you Rich.  I'll never forget those Krispy Kremes!
With hundreds of comments daily, it's daunting for me to comb through. So heartwarming to  know I'll find you guys here.

@Liana 

I get you but there was a revealer, of sorts - the down clues implicating stacking stuff. Once you open your mind to the idea of a rebus, you begin to spot such things. I used to be hopeless with rebuses but this one was quite gentle, IMO. 

I know this sound Stockholm sydrome-ish but if you force yourself to like rebuses, in time you may really enjoy them, or believe you do anyway, which feels the same 🤣

@Cathy Parrish 

I'm not a doc, but I thought so, too.

After getting the opening O, I was sure that the answer would be OB/GYN,...but how to make it fit?

@R.J. Smith 

SUBstack plus SUBSTANTIVE were my entrée to the trick, so I was fortunate to catch on early.

Otoh, I see a lot of commenters say HAYstack was their aha, and when I got to that section, I said to myself, "'HAYstack' kinda sounds familiar. Is that a thing?"

@John Carson 
Every time I go to Jersey Mike's I am forcibly reminded that I no longer live in NJ. They might as well be Jimmy John's.

I just want a real hoagie, dang it.

@Ian 

TATER is definitely baseball slang. It’s very inside baseball, though, and I am not surprised if many casual baseball fans haven’t heard of it. 

It’s obscure enough that I’m surprised to find out it’s what the clue is alluded to…if indeed it is.

@Jane Wheelaghan 

I’m not sure most Americans—unless they solve crosswords or live in Colorado—don’t know of ESTES Park; it is a rather small town. But it has useful crossword letters, so it has appeared many times. Previously, the word was clued to ESTES Kefauver, a senator and representative in the mid-20th century, and an unsuccessful vice presidential candidate in 1956. 

Fewer people would remember him these days, I guess, than know the Colorado town.

@Boodles 

As Deb mentioned in her column, this article explains how to do rebuses online:

<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/12/08/crosswords/rebus-crossword-puzzle.html" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/2023/12/08/crosswords/rebus-crossword-puzzle.html</a>

@Peter C 

Me too, but I think what Deb is saying is that the baseball reference is the more than one way to mash it. So we were half correct! 

I kind of just figured, well there are different ways to mash potatoes...  A mixer, a potato masher, a ricer, etc.
